            <fr:title text="Sylow's theorems">Sylow's theorems</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The Sylow theorems tell us about the existence and (non)uniqueness of <fr:link href="/gr-004S/" title="Sylow p-subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004S/" display-uri="gr-004S" type="local">Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link>s of a finite group. The numbering differs book to book, so we will be following <fr:link href="/i-martin-isaacs/" title="I. Martin Isaacs" uri="http://localhost:8000/i-martin-isaacs/" display-uri="i-martin-isaacs" type="local">I. Martin Isaacs</fr:link>'s <fr:link href="/isaacs-2008-finite/" title="Finite Group Theory" uri="http://localhost:8000/isaacs-2008-finite/" display-uri="isaacs-2008-finite" type="local">Finite Group Theory</fr:link> in describing these theorems.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>12</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/gr-004U/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>gr-004U</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/gr-004U/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Existence of a Sylow p-Subgroup">Existence of a Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-Subgroup</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source">I. Martin Isaacs <fr:link href="/isaacs-2008-finite/" title="Finite Group Theory" uri="http://localhost:8000/isaacs-2008-finite/" display-uri="isaacs-2008-finite" type="local">Finite Group Theory</fr:link> Theorem 1.7 (Sylow E-Theorem)</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a finite <fr:link href="/gr-000G/" title="Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000G/" display-uri="gr-000G" type="local">Group</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> be a prime number. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> has a Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>This may be viewed as a partial converse of <fr:link href="/gr-003K/" title="Lagrange's theorem" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-003K/" display-uri="gr-003K" type="local">Lagrange's theorem</fr:link>.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 

 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(Wielendt) Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|G|=p^{a}m]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\geq 0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\nmid  m]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega =\{A\subseteq  G\mid  |A|=p^{a}\}]]></fr:tex>. We see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> acts on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> by right multiplication. Since this is an action, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is partitioned into orbits, and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |]]></fr:tex> is the sum of the orbit sizes.</html:p>
<html:p>But
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[|\Omega |=\binom {p^{a}m}{p^{a}}\equiv  m\not \equiv 0\pmod {p},]]></fr:tex>
and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists some orbit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\in \mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H=G_{X}]]></fr:tex> be the <fr:link href="/gr-004C/" title="Stabilizer" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004C/" display-uri="gr-004C" type="local">Stabilizer</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|=|G|/|H|]]></fr:tex> by the <fr:link href="/gr-004G/" title="Orbit-Stabilizer theorem" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004G/" display-uri="gr-004G" type="local">Orbit-Stabilizer theorem</fr:link>, and since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> does not divide <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> but <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|G|]]></fr:tex>, we must conclude <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|]]></fr:tex>, and in particular <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}\leq |H|]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> stabilizes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> under right multiplication, we see if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[xH\subseteq  X]]></fr:tex>, and then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|=|xH|\leq |X|=p^{a}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}\leq |H|\leq  p^{a}]]></fr:tex>, we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|=p^{a}]]></fr:tex>, and this is a Sylow subgroup of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> as desired.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
