                <fr:title text="Sylow p-Subgroups are conjugate">Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-Subgroups are conjugate</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source">I. Martin Isaacs <fr:link href="/isaacs-2008-finite/" title="Finite Group Theory" uri="http://localhost:8000/isaacs-2008-finite/" display-uri="isaacs-2008-finite" type="local">Finite Group Theory</fr:link> Theorem 1.12 (Sylow C-Theorem)</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="/gr-004S/" title="Sylow p-subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004S/" display-uri="gr-004S" type="local">Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link>s of a finite <fr:link href="/gr-000G/" title="Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000G/" display-uri="gr-000G" type="local">Group</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, then there exists a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T=S^{g}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>This follows immediately from <fr:link href="/gr-004X/" title="Any p-subgroup is contained in a conjugate of a Sylow subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004X/" display-uri="gr-004X" type="local">Any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup is contained in a conjugate of a Sylow subgroup</fr:link> taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P=T]]></fr:tex> gives us <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T\subseteq  S^{g}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex>. Since both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> are Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroups, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|S|=|T|=|S^{g}|]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T=S^{g}]]></fr:tex> as desired.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 

 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>This may be viewed as a "finite analog" of a result in Lie theory where all maximal tori are conjugate to each other.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
