            <fr:title text="Any p-subgroup is contained in a conjugate of a Sylow subgroup">Any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup is contained in a conjugate of a Sylow subgroup</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>lemma</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">I. Martin Isaacs <fr:link href="/isaacs-2008-finite/" title="Finite Group Theory" uri="http://localhost:8000/isaacs-2008-finite/" display-uri="isaacs-2008-finite" type="local">Finite Group Theory</fr:link> Theorem 1.11</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> be an arbitrary <fr:link href="/gr-004O/" title="p-Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004O/" display-uri="gr-004O" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link> of a finite <fr:link href="/gr-000G/" title="Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000G/" display-uri="gr-000G" type="local">Group</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be any <fr:link href="/gr-004S/" title="Sylow p-subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004S/" display-uri="gr-004S" type="local">Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P\subseteq  S^{g}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega =\{Sx\mid  x\in  G\}]]></fr:tex> be the set of <fr:link href="/gr-003I/" title="Right cosets of a subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-003I/" display-uri="gr-003I" type="local">right cosets</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Observe <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |=[G : S]]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is a Sylow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>-subgroup of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. We know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> acts by right multiplication on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex>, and so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> acts too, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is partitioned into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbits. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, there must exist some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>By the <fr:link href="/gr-004G/" title="Orbit-Stabilizer theorem" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004G/" display-uri="gr-004G" type="local">Orbit-Stabilizer theorem</fr:link>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is the index in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> of some subgroup. It follows that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|P|]]></fr:tex>, which is a power of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is both a power of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and not divisible by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, so the only possibility is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|=1]]></fr:tex>. Since the members of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> are right cosets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, we can consider <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}=\{Sg\}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Sg]]></fr:tex> is alone in a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>-orbit, it follows that it is fixed under the action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Sgu=Sg]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  P]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[gu\in  Sg]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  g^{-1}Sg=S^{g}]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P\subseteq  S^{g}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
